== 20. Open Decisions Before Publication ==
To be resolved (ideally with retained Swiss counsel) before this policy is set effective. **#1 is time-sensitive and independent of the launch timeline.**
1. **⚠ TIME-SENSITIVE — public readability of submissions/reports.** Unauthenticated `GET /v1/jobs` and `/v1/jobs/{id}` mean submitted claims and reports may be readable by anyone who can reach the service. Make reports private by default (or a deliberate public/share-link design), restrict the list endpoint, and stop accepting submissions with personal/confidential content until fixed (§3.3, §11.1).
2. Alpha exposure status: **confirmed (2026-06-11) reachable by ~3 personally-known testers, ~8 jobs, no privacy-relevant inputs** — low risk. Publish and set this policy effective **before access is widened to any user not personally known to the team**; until then, give those testers the policy + a written warning.
3. Lawful basis confirmation, especially sensitive-data handling (§6).
4. Per-provider matrix — role (processor vs independent controller), transfer mechanism (DPF/SCC), and retention/training settings (§5.1, §13.1).
5. EU/EEA users in scope? → GDPR Art. 6/9 analysis + EU representative under Art. 27 (§11.5).
6. Submission **retention cap** + deletion workflow/SLA + backup-deletion propagation (§7, §9).
7. Production hosting: location, HTTPS enforcement, host log contents/retention, infrastructure-processor disclosure (§4.2, §7, §11.1).
8. Initial (lightweight) DPIA now; full DPIA before public launch; processing-activities register (§11.3, §11.4).
9. **Personality-rights / takedown workflow** for reports about identifiable persons (§6.2); source-excerpt/copyright safeguards (§5.3).
10. **Pre-submission click-through acceptance** of the Terms + Privacy Policy (see Terms of Service §1) — browsewrap is weak for the liability/indemnity/visibility/transfer clauses.
11. Effective date; EU-representative designation if in scope; **formal approval of these policies and the alpha risk acceptance by the competent Verein body** (§2, §11.5, §19).

